article.linkText: Summitt reaches peak as first women's coach with 800 wins
article.story:
KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Watch out Dean Smith. Pat Summitt isn't retiring anytime soon. Summitt became the first coach in women's college basketball history to win 800 career games when No. 5 Tennessee beat No. 25 DePaul 76-57 Tuesday night. Summitt is just the fourth men's or women's coach in Division I with 800 victories, joining Smith, Kentucky's Adolph Rupp and Jim Phelan at Mount Saint Mary's. Smith retired in 1997 as North Carolina's coach with a record 879 wins. Summitt's record stands at 800-161 in 29 seasons with six national championships, second only to John Wooden's 10 titles at UCLA. "I have no intention of getting out soon,'' Summitt, 50, told the fans in Thompson-Boling Arena during a postgame celebration. "I know everybody thinks I'm going to run out of gas. It's amazing. I love (coaching),'' she said later. "I do actually enjoy practice as much as games. Just the preparation that goes into it. At game time, I like to be able to watch the results of our teaching and coaching in practice situations. When I don't feel that way, I'm out of here.'' Tennessee (12-3) didn't allow for much suspense in whether Summitt would have to wait for the next game to reach the milestone. After the Blue Demons (12-4) tied it at 2 in the opening minute, it was all Tennessee. The Lady Vols slowly built a lead and then went on an 18-0 run in the first half. Reserve Brittany Jackson started it with two consecutive 3-pointers. Loree Moore caught a pass behind her, dribbled it around her back and drove to the basket and then Tye'sha Fluker capped the run on a putback that gave Tennessee a 36-10 lead with 5:19 remaining before halftime.
LEADERS OF WOMEN
As Pat Summitt added yet another notch to her legacy, ESPN.com paused to acknowledge the top active coaches in women's college basketball and the greatest of all-time. Summitt, the most recent member of the 800 Club, got Nancy Lieberman's vote as the best in the business.
  • Summitt flashback | Résumé
    		•
    The Lady Vols' lead didn't drop below 19 points the rest of the way. As the last seconds ticked away, the fans rose to their feet and chanted, "800, 800, 800!'' When the game ended, Summitt walked over and hugged DePaul coach Doug Bruno, then hugged each player as orange and white confetti rained on the court. School officials played a taped congratulatory message from Smith on the arena's video board and then presented Summitt with a cake, roses and game ball. Even though Summitt has set a new record for wins in women's college basketball, she said has more goals to achieve. That includes a seventh national title. "Our goal is to win the (Southeastern) conference again for the sixth consecutive time. We have the record of five, but we want to make sure no one else catches up with us,'' Summitt said. "It's just to keep getting better. Our basketball team has pretty much the same goal every year. We want to be in Atlanta and we want to cut down the nets.'' And Summitt was proud of her team's efforts toward that goal. Ashley Robinson led Tennessee in scoring with 12 points while Shyra Ely had 11 and Gwen Jackson added 10. The Blue Demons were led by Khara Smith's 18 points and Charlene Smith's 14. DePaul had trouble against Tennessee's much bigger post players and couldn't get any good looks from beyond the arc. The Blue Demons, outrebounded 49-26, played only two players over 6-feet tall while the Lady Vols had seven. The Lady Vols increased their record over DePaul to 13-0 and snapped the Blue Demon's five-game winning streak. Despite the lopsided score, the Lady Vols didn't hold back. Summitt continued to substitute players and yell out directions and encouragement from the bench. "When the game started the players were in control of the game and getting Coach Summitt to 800 wins,'' senior Kara Lawson said. "We wanted to make sure her 800th win was something that she would be proud of with our effort.'' Summitt was hired as a graduate teaching assistant and women's coach at Tennessee in 1974 at age 22. She earned her first career victory in the team's second game in January 1975. It took Summitt just four years to reach her 100th win on Jan. 13, 1979, at North Carolina State. She won her 300th at home on Jan. 4, 1987, against North Carolina. Summitt picked up No. 500 against Ohio State at the inaugural State Farm Tip-Off Classic in Jackson, Tenn., in 1993. The Lady Vols won 85-62 at Wisconsin on Dec. 5, 1999, as Summitt joined Texas coach Jody Conradt as the only two women's college basketball coaches to reach 700 wins. Conradt now trails Summitt with 797 wins.
